Construct the dataset for modelling

mort_count <- fread("ma_mort_count.csv")
exposure <- fread("daily_exposure.csv")
dt <- merge(mort_count, exposure, by = "date", all.x = TRUE)
names(dt)
 [1] "date"   "CVD"    "MI"     "CHF"    "stroke" "TOT"    "dow"    "lbeta"  "temp"  
[10] "rh"    
dt[, date:= as.Date(date)]
head(dt)

Here we get the prepared data named dt for daily death count along with daily exposure.

We would deal with the missing values in the following chunk: do interpolate using splines with the imputeTS R package.

paste("Exposure records: start:", exposure[1, date], "end:", exposure[.N, date])
[1] "Exposure records: start: 2000-01-01 end: 2014-02-28"
paste("Mortality data: start:", mort_count[1, date], "end:", mort_count[.N, date])
[1] "Mortality data: start: 2000-01-01 end: 2015-12-31"
dt <- dt[date<="2014-02-28",] # drop those without exposure info
setorder(dt, date)
dt[, `:=`(lbeta = na_interpolation(lbeta, option = "spline"),
          temp = na_interpolation(temp, option = "spline"),
          rh = na_interpolation(rh, option = "spline"))]
cat("Whether the data contains any NAs: ", any(is.na(dt)))
Whether the data contains any NAs:  FALSE

Model analysis: beta radiation and daily death count

dt[, time:=1:.N]
modCVD_check <- gam(CVD ~ s(time, bs="cr", k=77, fx=TRUE) + s(lbeta, bs="cr", fx=FALSE) + 
                     s(temp, bs="cr", fx=FALSE) + s(rh, bs="cr", fx=FALSE) + as.factor(dow),
                   family = quasipoisson, data = dt)
